{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16137"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16137"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.38,0.03,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8828"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7881"},{"type":"tags","id":"8543"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21058"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, significant cardiovascular adaptations occur to support the developing fetus and prepare for childbirth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most significantly increased blood component during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plasma volume","Red blood cell volume","White blood cell volume","Platelet volume","Albumin concentration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, \u003Cstrong\u003Eplasma volume\u003C/strong\u003E increases by approximately 30-50% above non-pregnant levels. This increase is proportionally greater than the increase in \u003Cstrong\u003Ered blood cell volume\u003C/strong\u003E, which rises by only 20-30%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ewhite blood cell volume\u003C/strong\u003E shows only minor fluctuations during pregnancy. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet volume\u003C/strong\u003E typically remains stable or may slightly decrease. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin concentration\u003C/strong\u003E actually decreases due to the dilutional effect of the expanded plasma volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe disproportionate increase in plasma volume compared to red blood cells results in physiological anaemia of pregnancy. This is a normal adaptation that reduces blood viscosity and improves placental perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During pregnancy, plasma volume increases by 30-50% while red cell volume increases by only 20-30%.","The disproportionate increase in plasma volume relative to red blood cells leads to physiological anaemia of pregnancy."],"references":["Vricella LK. Emerging understanding and measurement of plasma volume expansion in pregnancy. Am J Clin Nutr. 2017 Dec;106(Suppl 6):1620S-1625S. doi: 10.3945/ajcn.117.155903. Epub 2017 Oct 25. PMID: 29070547; PMCID: PMC5701717.","Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162.","Aguree S, Gernand AD. Plasma volume expansion across healthy pregnancy: a systematic review and meta-analysis of longitudinal studies. BMC Pregnancy Childbirth. 2019 Dec 19;19(1):508. doi: 10.1186/s12884-019-2619-6. PMID: 31856759; PMCID: PMC6924087.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16137"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T21:25:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T21:26:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8828"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64041"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30",